div.head: To al that affect the famous exerciſe of ARCHERIE frequenting Finſburie fieldes.
div.p:
SHooting in the long bow being of it ſelfe very laudable, and our Engliſh nation in all ages ſurpaſſing therein all others, yea neither the Getes, Seythes, Parthians, Sarmathians, Armiaſpes famous for that quality, nor any other people could become equall with Engliſh Archers. And yet (a matter to be lamented) this laudable exerciſe of late dayes hath become cold in moſt places of this land, famous Londō retaining the moſt ardēt deſire to maintaine the ſame, as appeareth by the daily concourſe of Citizens, to their great commendations, in diuerſe companies in the conuenient fields about the citie, but moſt eſpecially in that choiſe place Finſburie,
moſt eſpecially garniſhed with many beautifull Markes in this little Treatiſe Alphabetically mentioned, whereby the benefactors therein ſhall haue perpetuall memorie recorded by the titles of their ſeuerall erections.

And for that euery hand ought to bring ſome portion of helpe towards the preſeruation and increaſe of ſo commendable actiuitie, we haue (by the helpe of our friends) caſt in alſo our mite, wiſhing it to worke a continuing in the old, and a growing goodwill in ſuch yong beginners as would become skilfull in this most acceptable qualitie, for whoſe ſakes this litle worke is reuiewed, reuiued and republiſhed, with ſuch neceſſary, eaſie, and helpfull obſeruations as may ſeeme beſt to ſatisfie thoſe that are deſirous to come to knowledge in the Markes.

div.head: Rules touching the vſe of the Treatiſe.
div.p: 1 First, you must note, that ſundrie Markes haue two or three wordes for their names, looke for the marke alwaies in the firſt word, as in the Kings Mace, looke not for Mace but for Kings: alſo the Houſe of Lancaſter, looke for Houſe not for Lancaſter, and ſo in the reſt.
2 And it is further to be noted, that the firſt number ſheweth the ſcores, the ſecond the yards: you muſt ſhoote long ayme, becauſe this is ſet downe by meaſure of the line

3 Againe you muſt note, that wee haue ſet downe the markes to be taken all going into the fields, and if you be coming homeward, looke for the marke you ſhoote at, and not for the marke you ſtand at. And we haue placed from
euery marke all the marks from the left hand to the right, leauing out none from 9. ſcore to 18. or 19. ſcore. And when a marke is found along a banke, you muſt alwayes looke for the marke from the Weſt towards the Eaſt.

4 Alſo for the aide of yong ſhooters wee: haue ſet downe in the ende of the booke a Table of the names of all the marks, with direction in what page to find them, for the eaſe of thoſe that are vnacquainted with the names of the markes.

For the better aduertiſement of ſuch as are not acquainted with the order of the game and cuſtome of the field, wherby often ariſe controuerſies, and diuerſe times grow raſh and vnaduiſed othes, to the derogation of Gods glory, we haue thought it good to ſet downe ſuch orders as are ſitteſt to be obſerued in this exerciſe.
1 Firſt for the finding of your marke, it muſt be within euery mans reach. Alſo the preciſe naming of your marke preuenteth much cauill.
2 Secondly, for whites you may haue as many as you will, ſo they be all forwards, and if you ſhoote at anie looſe white, and it be ſtriken out of ſight, it is no marke.
3 Thirdly, for the highest of ſtakes, if the wood be aboue the pin, you are to meaſure at the wood, although the pin hath bene put in for the ſame purpoſe.
4 Fourthly, if you finde a buſh or a blacke, whatſoeuer you finde higheſt in it, being within the compaſſe of the marke, you are to take it for the height.

5 Fiftly, for all trees you are to meaſure at foote and pole, except in the naming of it you ſay, at the naile in ſuch a tree, or hole in ſuch a tree, or being a tree of ſo ſmall height, that you may
reach the top of it with halfe your bowe, then you may take the higheſt.

6 Sixtly, if there be ſo nigh a ſhoote that it cannot be giuen by the contrarie ſide, or by another companie, then the better of them two is to win the ſhoote at the next marke, and not to let it lye dead to the aduantage of the contrarie ſide. If in meaſuring of the ſhoote, by haſte the marke is ſtirred, he is to loſe the ſhoote that meaſureth it.
7 Seuenthly, when you come to the marke and claime two, and the contrary ſides draw their arrowes, & when your mate comes he ſaith his would win too, you are to win no more then you claime.
8 Laſtly, if you name one marke and ſhoote at another, you are to loſe your ſhoot, and they are to follow at the mark named.
